i## title: My Nix exploration	/	tilde.team	70
i## date: "2024-06-24"	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i/nix_logo.svg	/	tilde.team	70
I/nix_logo.svg	/~nagi/nix_logo.svg	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iHere I share some notes and other things I've learned about	/	tilde.team	70
iNix that I find interesting. The content of this post is	/	tilde.team	70
imainly about me learning Nix, it's not about understanding	/	tilde.team	70
ithe whole tool and language.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iAlso, it's important to note that I use Nix as a non-NixOS	/	tilde.team	70
iuser.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## What is Nix?	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iNix is actually several things! It's a cross platform	/	tilde.team	70
ipackage manager. It would be a little more accurate to say	/	tilde.team	70
ithat it's a deployment tool used as a package manager.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iAnd it's also a purely functional programming language,	/	tilde.team	70
idynamically typed and lazily evaluated.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## Learning the programming language	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI started by learning the basics of the language and then	/	tilde.team	70
iwent on to explore it in a bit more depth.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i### The basics	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI read Nix language basics and to get used to the language I	/	tilde.team	70
ipractised with A tour of Nix which has several levels of	/	tilde.team	70
idifficulty from "easy" to "hard".	/	tilde.team	70
hNix language basics	URL:https://nix.dev/tutorials/nix-language#reading-nix-language	nix.dev	443
hA tour of Nix	URL:https://nixcloud.io/tour	nixcloud.io	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iOne interesting thing about this language is that it has	/	tilde.team	70
ionly one argument per function. To simulate several	/	tilde.team	70
iarguments, you can, for example, write a function with one	/	tilde.team	70
iargument that returns a function with one argument that	/	tilde.team	70
ireturns a function with one argument, and so on. The syntax	/	tilde.team	70
iof the language makes it easy to do this.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI was taught that it has a name, it's called Currying. It's	/	tilde.team	70
ithe transformation of a function with several arguments into	/	tilde.team	70
ia function with one argument that returns a function on the	/	tilde.team	70
irest of the arguments. Here's an example with arguments 3	/	tilde.team	70
iand 4.	/	tilde.team	70
hCurrying	URL:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Currying	en.wikipedia.org	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
inix-repl> (a: b: a + b) 3 4	/	tilde.team	70
i7	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iA Python equivalent might be something like the following.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i>>> (lambda a: lambda b: a + b)(3)(4)	/	tilde.team	70
i7	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iAnother solution that is often used, particularly in	/	tilde.team	70
iNixpkgs, is to have an attribute set as a parameter to the	/	tilde.team	70
ifunction, and to use the attributes as arguments. For	/	tilde.team	70
iexample, this might look like the expression below.	/	tilde.team	70
hNixpkgs	URL:https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs	github.com	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
inix-repl> ({a, b}: a + b){a = 3; b = 4;}	/	tilde.team	70
i7	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i### Fake dynamic binding	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iAlthough the blog post How to Fake Dynamic Binding in Nix	/	tilde.team	70
italks about this very well, I find it interesting to offer	/	tilde.team	70
imy own thoughts and approach.	/	tilde.team	70
hHow to Fake Dynamic Binding in Nix	URL:http://r6.ca/blog/20140422T142911Z.html	r6.ca	80
i	/	tilde.team	70
iThe language is statically scoped, i.e. binding decisions	/	tilde.team	70
iare made according to the scope at declaration time.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iLet's look at the rec keyword, which allows an attribute set	/	tilde.team	70
ito access its own attributes (recursive binding). Here's an	/	tilde.team	70
iexample.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
inix-repl> rec { a = 1; b = a + 1;}	/	tilde.team	70
i{	/	tilde.team	70
i  a = 1;	/	tilde.team	70
i  b = 2;	/	tilde.team	70
i}	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iThis is an interesting feature, but it remains static	/	tilde.team	70
ibecause the binding is done before the runtime. This poses	/	tilde.team	70
iproblems, particularly when it comes to overriding	/	tilde.team	70
iattributes, as shown in the example below.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
inix-repl> rec { a = 1; b = a + 1; } // { a = 10; }	/	tilde.team	70
i{	/	tilde.team	70
i  a = 10;	/	tilde.team	70
i  b = 2;	/	tilde.team	70
i}	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iIn this example, we would like b to be equal to 11, not 2.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iTo solve this problem, we can look at the concept of a fixed	/	tilde.team	70
ipoint. A fixed point is a value of x that validates the	/	tilde.team	70
iequation x = f(x).	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iWe can therefore write the following function.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
inix-repl> fix = f: let	/	tilde.team	70
i  result = f result;	/	tilde.team	70
iin	/	tilde.team	70
i  result	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iSo here we have the function fix which takes a function f as	/	tilde.team	70
ia parameter and returns the fixed point result of the	/	tilde.team	70
ifunction f.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iYou might be tempted to say that the f function calls itself	/	tilde.team	70
iad infinitum (f(f(f(f(..))))), but Nix evaluates expressions	/	tilde.team	70
ilazily, so this isn't the case.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iWe can literally see that the f function returns a fixed	/	tilde.team	70
ipoint (result), because result = f result, which respects	/	tilde.team	70
ithe definition of a fixed point.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iThe fix function will allow us to emulate the rec keyword,	/	tilde.team	70
ias shown in the example below.	/	tilde.team	70
inix-repl> fix (self: { a = 3; b = 4; c = self.a + self.b; })	/	tilde.team	70
i{	/	tilde.team	70
i  a = 3;	/	tilde.team	70
i  b = 4;	/	tilde.team	70
i  c = 7;	/	tilde.team	70
i}	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iTo better understand how it works, I've written the result	/	tilde.team	70
iof the fix function differently with the argument used	/	tilde.team	70
ipreviously.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
inix-repl> let	/	tilde.team	70
i  result = { a = 3; b = 4; c = result.a + result.b;};	/	tilde.team	70
iin	/	tilde.team	70
i  { a = 3; b = 4; c = result.a + result.b;}	/	tilde.team	70
i{	/	tilde.team	70
i  a = 3;	/	tilde.team	70
i  b = 4;	/	tilde.team	70
i  c = 7;	/	tilde.team	70
i}	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iFinally, I've written the following function, which will	/	tilde.team	70
iallow the attributes to be overridden dynamically as	/	tilde.team	70
iinitially intended.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
inix-repl> fix = let	/	tilde.team	70
i  fixWithOverride = f: overrides: let	/	tilde.team	70
i      result = (f result) // overrides;	/	tilde.team	70
i    in	/	tilde.team	70
i      result // { override = x: fixWithOverride f x; };	/	tilde.team	70
iin	/	tilde.team	70
if: fixWithOverride f {}	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iattrFunction = self: { a = 3; b = 4; c = self.a+self.b; }	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iattrFunctionFixedPoint = fix attrFunction	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
inix-repl> attrFunctionFixedPoint	/	tilde.team	70
i{	/	tilde.team	70
i  a = 3;	/	tilde.team	70
i  b = 4;	/	tilde.team	70
i  c = 7;	/	tilde.team	70
i  override = «lambda override @ «string»:5:30»;	/	tilde.team	70
i}	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
inix-repl> attrFunctionFixedPoint.override { b = 1; }	/	tilde.team	70
i{	/	tilde.team	70
i  a = 3;	/	tilde.team	70
i  b = 1;	/	tilde.team	70
i  c = 4;	/	tilde.team	70
i  override = «lambda override @ «string»:5:30»;	/	tilde.team	70
i}	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## The essential Nix tool	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iAs already mentioned, the main use of Nix is cross platform	/	tilde.team	70
ipackage management. In this section I'm just trying to share	/	tilde.team	70
iand summarise some of the essential parts of my notes. If	/	tilde.team	70
iyou want more details, I recommend you read the excellent	/	tilde.team	70
iNix Pills. It's rather long but well worth the read!	/	tilde.team	70
hNix Pills	URL:https://nixos.org/guides/nix-pills/	nixos.org	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
i### How does it work ?	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iTo sum up, I'd say that the Nix language has a very	/	tilde.team	70
iinteresting native function called derivation (see	/	tilde.team	70
idocumentation) on which many Nix expressions are based. I'm	/	tilde.team	70
inot going to redefine the term because the documentation has	/	tilde.team	70
ia very comprehensible version, but the important thing to	/	tilde.team	70
iremember is that a derivation is a construction	/	tilde.team	70
ispecification, it's an immutable Nix building block. With	/	tilde.team	70
ianother package manager, you could see it as a literal	/	tilde.team	70
ipackage.	/	tilde.team	70
hsee documentation	URL:https://nix.dev/manual/nix/2.22/language/derivations	nix.dev	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iNix technology will enable us to build these derivations, in	/	tilde.team	70
ithe following stages.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i/nix_graph.png	/	tilde.team	70
I/nix_graph.png	/~nagi/nix_graph.png	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iThe .drv files contain specifications on how to build the	/	tilde.team	70
iderivation, they are intermediate files comparable to .o	/	tilde.team	70
ifiles, and the .nix files are comparable to .c files.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iThe construction result is immutable and will be stored in	/	tilde.team	70
i/nix/store/, a synchronisation with the SQLite database. I	/	tilde.team	70
isaid it was immutable, in fact it is because Nix creates a	/	tilde.team	70
ihash for the path in the /nix/store/ from the input	/	tilde.team	70
iderivation (not from the construction result).	/	tilde.team	70
hSQLite	URL:https://www.sqlite.org/	www.sqlite.org	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iIt's pretty hard to imagine all this, so I'll give you a	/	tilde.team	70
iconcrete example. Let's imagine I want to create a	/	tilde.team	70
iderivation for the famous software GNU Hello. The Nix	/	tilde.team	70
iderivation could look something like this.	/	tilde.team	70
hGNU Hello	URL:https://www.gnu.org/software/hello/	www.gnu.org	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
i# default.nix	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
ilet	/	tilde.team	70
i  pkgs = import <nixpkgs> { };	/	tilde.team	70
iin	/	tilde.team	70
i  {	/	tilde.team	70
i    hello = pkgs.stdenv.mkDerivation {	/	tilde.team	70
i      pname = "hello";	/	tilde.team	70
i      version = "2.12.1";	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i      src = fetchTarball {	/	tilde.team	70
i        url = "https://ftp.gnu.org/gnu/hello/hello-	/	tilde.team	70
i2.12.1.tar.gz";	/	tilde.team	70
i        sha256 =	/	tilde.team	70
i"1kJjhtlsAkpNB7f6tZEs+dbKd8z7KoNHyDHEJ0tmhnc=";	/	tilde.team	70
i      };	/	tilde.team	70
i    };	/	tilde.team	70
i  }	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i“The mkDerivation function is based on the derivation	/	tilde.team	70
ibuiltin function.”	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iIt can be built with the following command.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
inix-build	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iThe build result has been created in	/	tilde.team	70
i/nix/store/x9cc4jsylk5q01iaxmxf941b59chws5h-hello-2.12.1 and a	/	tilde.team	70
isymbolic link named result pointing to this folder has been	/	tilde.team	70
icreated in the current folder. We can then find the binary	/	tilde.team	70
iin ./result/bin/hello.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iBefore the build, a .drv file was created, which can be	/	tilde.team	70
ifound by running the following command.	/	tilde.team	70
inix derivation show ./result | jq "keys[0]"	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iThe full path to the .drv file is found in the first key of	/	tilde.team	70
ithe JSON object, so the path to the .drv file is	/	tilde.team	70
i/nix/store/dp5z62k3chf019biikg77p2acmz17phx-hello-2.12.1.drv.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iAs it is in binary format we can use nix derivation show to	/	tilde.team	70
idisplay the construction information it contains with the	/	tilde.team	70
ifollowing command.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
inix derivation show (nix derivation show ./result | jq	/	tilde.team	70
i"keys[0]" | tr -d "\"")	/	tilde.team	70
i# Or	/	tilde.team	70
inix derivation show	/	tilde.team	70
i/nix/store/dp5z62k3chf019biikg77p2acmz17phx-hello-2.12.1.drv	/	tilde.team	70
i# ^	/	tilde.team	70
i# | Same output	/	tilde.team	70
i# v	/	tilde.team	70
inix derivation show ./result	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i### Nixpkgs	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iIn the Nix expression used previously (the GNU Hello	/	tilde.team	70
iderivation), I used the mkDerivation function from stdenv.	/	tilde.team	70
hGNU Hello	URL:https://www.gnu.org/software/hello/	www.gnu.org	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iThis function is not builtin, it comes from the pkgs	/	tilde.team	70
iidentifier which has the value import <nixpkgs> { };.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iBefore explaining this import, I think it's very important	/	tilde.team	70
ito understand what Nixpkgs is. It's a Git repository that	/	tilde.team	70
icontains all the Nix expressions and modules. When this	/	tilde.team	70
ifolder is evaluated, it produces an attribute set containing	/	tilde.team	70
istdenv, which is itself an attribute set containing our	/	tilde.team	70
imkDerivation function.	/	tilde.team	70
hNixpkgs	URL:https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs	github.com	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iGetting back to pkgs, <nixpkgs> is just a special Nix	/	tilde.team	70
isyntax, which, when evaluated, gives a path to a folder	/	tilde.team	70
icontaining a collection of Nix expressions, i.e. Nixpkgs.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iIncidentally <nixpkgs> has an equivalence in Nix as shown	/	tilde.team	70
ibelow.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
inix-repl> <nixpkgs>	/	tilde.team	70
i/home/nagi/.nix-defexpr/channels/nixpkgs	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
inix-repl> builtins.findFile builtins.nixPath "nixpkgs"	/	tilde.team	70
i/home/nagi/.nix-defexpr/channels/nixpkg	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
inix-repl> :p builtins.nixPath	/	tilde.team	70
i[	/	tilde.team	70
i  {	/	tilde.team	70
i    path = "/home/nagi/.nix-defexpr/channels";	/	tilde.team	70
i    prefix = "";	/	tilde.team	70
i  }	/	tilde.team	70
i]	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i### Managing multiple Python versions	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iOne of the advantages of Nix is that it naturally offers the	/	tilde.team	70
ipossibility of managing several versions of the same	/	tilde.team	70
iapplication. Taking Python as an example, let's say I want a	/	tilde.team	70
iNix shell with version 3.7 and version 3.13.	/	tilde.team	70
hPython	URL:https://www.python.org/	www.python.org	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iTo do this, we can check for which version of Nixpkgs Python	/	tilde.team	70
iwas built on version 3.7 and target a specific version of	/	tilde.team	70
iNixpkgs in our Nix expression.	/	tilde.team	70
hNixpkgs	URL:https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs	github.com	443
hNixpkgs	URL:https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs	github.com	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iTo do this, there's the flox tool which works very well, but	/	tilde.team	70
ito make it easier to understand I prefer to use nixhub.io.	/	tilde.team	70
hflox	URL:https://floxdev.com/	floxdev.com	443
hnixhub.io	URL:https://www.nixhub.io	www.nixhub.io	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iSo I'm looking for a version of the Nix packages that	/	tilde.team	70
icorresponds to Python version 3.7, and I find	/	tilde.team	70
inixpkgs/aca0bbe791c220f8360bd0dd8e9dce161253b341#python37.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i# shell.nix	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
ilet	/	tilde.team	70
i  pkgs = import (fetchTarball	/	tilde.team	70
i"https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/tarball/nixos-23.11") { };	/	tilde.team	70
i  nixpkgs-python = import (fetchTarball	/	tilde.team	70
i"https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/archive/aca0bbe791c220f8360bd0dd8e9dce161253b341.tar.gz")	/	tilde.team	70
i{ };	/	tilde.team	70
iin	/	tilde.team	70
i  pkgs.mkShell {	/	tilde.team	70
i    buildInputs = [	/	tilde.team	70
i      nixpkgs-python.python37	/	tilde.team	70
i      pkgs.python313	/	tilde.team	70
i    ];	/	tilde.team	70
i  }	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iYou can build Python derivations and enter a Nix shell with	/	tilde.team	70
ithe following command.	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
inix-shell	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iAnd we see that we have access to the two versions requested	/	tilde.team	70
iwith the commands python3.7 and python3.13 !	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## A Virtual environment in Python with Nix flakes	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iI've recently created a development environment with Nix	/	tilde.team	70
iflakes (see documentation), it's very handy as it provides a	/	tilde.team	70
iready to use environment for Python 3.11 with the desired	/	tilde.team	70
imodules.	/	tilde.team	70
hsee documentation	URL:https://nixos.wiki/wiki/Flakes	nixos.wiki	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
iBelow is a Nix expression I wrote for the Python module	/	tilde.team	70
icallviz, it has all the necessary dependencies and a virtual	/	tilde.team	70
iPython environment.	/	tilde.team	70
hcallviz	URL:https://pypi.org/project/callviz/	pypi.org	443
i	/	tilde.team	70
i# flake.nix	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i{	/	tilde.team	70
i  inputs = {	/	tilde.team	70
i    nixpkgs.url = "github:NixOS/nixpkgs/nixpkgs-unstable";	/	tilde.team	70
i  };	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i  outputs =	/	tilde.team	70
i    { self, nixpkgs }:	/	tilde.team	70
i    let	/	tilde.team	70
i      supportedSystems = [	/	tilde.team	70
i        "x86_64-linux"	/	tilde.team	70
i        "aarch64-linux"	/	tilde.team	70
i        "x86_64-darwin"	/	tilde.team	70
i        "aarch64-darwin"	/	tilde.team	70
i      ];	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i      forEachSupportedSystem =	/	tilde.team	70
i        f: nixpkgs.lib.genAttrs supportedSystems (system: f	/	tilde.team	70
i{ pkgs = import nixpkgs { inherit system; }; });	/	tilde.team	70
i    in	/	tilde.team	70
i    {	/	tilde.team	70
i      # ...	/	tilde.team	70
i      # I usually also declare a default package, a code	/	tilde.team	70
ichecker and formatter	/	tilde.team	70
i      devShells = forEachSupportedSystem (	/	tilde.team	70
i        { pkgs }:	/	tilde.team	70
i        {	/	tilde.team	70
i          default = pkgs.mkShell {	/	tilde.team	70
i            venvDir = ".venv";	/	tilde.team	70
i            packages =	/	tilde.team	70
i              with pkgs;	/	tilde.team	70
i              [	/	tilde.team	70
i                python3	/	tilde.team	70
i                graphviz	/	tilde.team	70
i              ]	/	tilde.team	70
i              ++ (with pkgs.python3Packages; [	/	tilde.team	70
i                pip	/	tilde.team	70
i                venvShellHook	/	tilde.team	70
i                graphviz	/	tilde.team	70
i              ]);	/	tilde.team	70
i          };	/	tilde.team	70
i        }	/	tilde.team	70
i      );	/	tilde.team	70
i    };	/	tilde.team	70
i}	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iNote that the default package and the default development	/	tilde.team	70
ishell are compatible with all systems (supportedSystems)!	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iTo realise the derivations and enter the Nix shell, I can	/	tilde.team	70
irun the following command.	/	tilde.team	70
inix develop	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
i## Nixpkgs contribution	/	tilde.team	70
i	/	tilde.team	70
iOnce I'd finished exploring and learning Nix, I wanted to	/	tilde.team	70
imake a package for Super Mario War and add it to Nixpkgs.	/	tilde.team	70
hSuper Mario War	URL:http://smwstuff.net/game	smwstuff.net	80
hNixpkgs	URL:https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs	github.com	443
